In the realm where whimsy meets the fray,
Where laughter reigns and colours play,
There lies a world both bold and bright,
A carnival of joy, a pure delight.

In Fall Guys' realm, the stage is set,
With obstacles that challenge, yet
The little beans, so full of glee,
Embark on quests to reach victory.

They bound and tumble, stumble, soar,
Through dizzying heights and corridors,
Their jelly legs a comical sight,
As they chase the crown with all their might.

Amidst the chaos, friendships bloom,
In this realm where joy consumes,
For every fall is met with cheer,
And every triumph draws them near.

With costumes wild and patterns grand,
They navigate this whimsical land,
Through seas of slime and towering walls,
Their determination never stalls.

So let us join this merry throng,
In Fall Guys' world, where we belong,
And in the falling, find our grace,

Overview:
Fall Guys is a delightful blend of chaotic gameplay, colorful aesthetics, and addictive competition. Developed by Mediatonic, this multiplayer party game throws you into a frenzied obstacle course with dozens of other jellybean-like characters, each vying to be the last one standing. Released in 2020, Fall Guys quickly gained popularity for its accessible mechanics and uproarious moments.

Gameplay:
The premise is simple: navigate through a series of obstacle courses, challenges, and minigames while contending with fellow contestants. Whether it's dodging giant rolling balls, avoiding pitfalls, or racing to the finish line, every round is a test of skill, luck, and sheer determination. The controls are easy to grasp, making it accessible to players of all skill levels.

Visuals and Sound:
Fall Guys boasts vibrant, whimsical graphics that bring its wacky world to life. The character designs are charmingly goofy, and the various stages are filled with bright colors and playful animations. The soundtrack is equally upbeat, adding to the game's infectious energy and keeping players engaged throughout.

Replayability:
One of Fall Guys' greatest strengths is its replayability. With a multitude of courses and game modes, no two matches are ever the same. The unpredictable nature of the gameplay ensures that even seasoned players will encounter fresh challenges and surprises with each playthrough. Additionally, regular updates and seasonal events introduce new content, ensuring that the game stays relevant and exciting over time.

Community and Multiplayer Experience:
Fall Guys thrives on its multiplayer experience, fostering a sense of camaraderie and competition among players. Whether teaming up with friends or facing off against strangers, the game offers endless opportunities for laughter and memorable moments. The supportive community further enhances the experience, with players sharing strategies, memes, and epic gameplay highlights across social media platforms.

Final Thoughts:
Fall Guys is a delightful romp that delivers hours of laughter and entertainment. Its accessible gameplay, colorful visuals, and chaotic multiplayer action make it a standout title in the party game genre. While occasional server issues and matchmaking hiccups may dampen the experience, the sheer fun and excitement of Fall Guys make it a must-play for gamers of all ages. Grab your jellybean avatar and dive into the hilarious mayhem   just be prepared to laugh, shout, and maybe even rage a little along the way.

Fall Guys is a vibrant and chaotic mash-up that feels like Mario Party and Fortnite had a wildly colorful baby. It's a game that combines the whimsical, party-game fun of Mario Party with the competitive, last-one-standing excitement of Fortnite ‚Äì and it does so in a brilliantly entertaining way.

From the moment you start, you're plunged into a series of zany and unpredictable mini-games, each more delightful and wacky than the last. The courses are a wild ride of obstacles, challenges, and surprises, ensuring that no two games ever feel the same. The bright, playful graphics and upbeat soundtrack add to the game's cheerful and lighthearted atmosphere.

What sets Fall Guys apart is its accessibility and appeal to players of all ages and skill levels. Whether you're a seasoned gamer looking for some casual fun or a party-game enthusiast, you'll find yourself laughing, cheering, and sometimes shouting at your screen in the best way possible.

In essence, Fall Guys is a joyful, chaotic experience that brilliantly captures the essence of both Mario Party's fun and Fortnite's competitive edge. It's a game that brings people together for some good, old-fashioned fun ‚Äì a perfect blend of party game madness and battle royale thrill.

Feel the exhilaration as you stand on the edge of an inflatable obstacle, heart pounding, and nerves electrified with anticipation in Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout. Step into a whimsical wonderland where your jellybean-like character navigates through a labyrinth of challenges, each step a heart-stopping leap from platform to platform. Picture yourself on the precipice, hands sweating as your character faces the jump of a lifetime, evoking a sense of both excitement and trepidation. This multiplayer spectacle is not just a game; it's a carnival of chaos that transcends traditional gaming experiences. With every daring move, you join a throng of 60 contestants, bouncing, flopping, and hurdling through an unpredictable series of obstacles. The vibrant graphics and playful sound effects create an atmosphere of pure joy and camaraderie, turning every match into a pulse-pounding adventure where triumph is never guaranteed. Fall Guys is a rollercoaster of emotions, from the nerve-wracking anticipation of a challenging jump to the euphoria of claiming the coveted crown. Get ready to lose yourself in the adrenaline-fueled world of Fall Guys, where every obstacle is a story waiting to unfold, and every victory is a testament to your agility and determination.

Fall Guys is a blast, but the repetitive cycle of playing the same 5 maps can be a drawback. While the occasional new map adds freshness, the real buzzkill is dealing with Epic's frustratingly lackluster customer support.

Fall Guys becomes highly enjoyable once you grasp the mechanics and strategies for winning. I personally prefer an aggressive playstyle, engaging in playful confrontations by grabbing and outmaneuvering opponents. It adds an extra layer of excitement to identify skilled players and attempt to outsmart them.

While the game has had several enjoyable years with consistent level updates, there is a sense of disappointment as it appears that no new levels are on the horizon, leaving the game in a stagnant state. Despite this, I still recommend the game for its overall fun experience, though it is disheartening that we may not see any fresh levels in the future.

First, SBMM was forced into solo show (and as of January 2024, it was implemented into squads show as well) despite the massive backlash from the community, then we had to suffer through the egregious and unnecessary removal of the majority of rounds known as "vaulting", and now, to avoid major repercussions for their own greed and incompetence, Epic Games is laying off many of its employees, including most of the core people behind Mediatonic and Fall Guys, effectively squashing any hope this title has on bouncing back to relevancy and positive reputation. 

On top of that, many critical bugs and issues (awful performance and crashes on Switch, abysmal round and show variety, aforementioned unfair SBMM in solos and squads, matchmaking getting stuck on "waiting for server", invisible faceplates, physics glitches, desync, level publishing errors, creative levels failing to download, infinite loading bug, etc.) have yet to be resolved, let alone acknowledged, by what remains of the dev team. Each new update to this game literally introduces more bugs than it fixes.

The game has also been needlessly downgraded across all platforms in order for it to (barley) run on the Switch. It just isn't right for all players to suffer these setbacks when it's beyond their control. And no, as underpowered as the Switch is, it's not Nintendo's fault that these developers can't optimize the game sufficiently for the console.

The only slightly positive thing that's happened to this game recently is that they're slowly unvaulting levels, but it's a case of too little too late; said unvaulted levels rarely appear due to horrible round selection parameters. Also, some of the unvaulted levels are STILL broken, if not simply buggy in some areas, which sometimes has led such levels right back into the vault. Their negligence to keep these rounds glitch-free and playable after the rounds have been removed from the game for so long ultimately defeats the purpose of the whole vaulting fiasco, which was, in MT's words, to improve stability and deliver bug fixes more efficiently.

This is why we need to have more legislation for the gaming industry (and the entertainment industry as a whole). Corporations should not and can not get away with screwing over well-established IPs forever with their profits-first mindset and malicious lack of quality control.

I had hesitation on viewing Epic Games as an evil corporation in the past, but that has changed following the downfall of this game. 

Please do not support these companies anymore if you ever want them to be held accountable for their abuse of beloved franchises.

FALL GUYS:

Rating: 7.5/10

Fall Guys is a fun F2P multiplayer game that deviates from typical free-to-play games. Although it has minor flaws, Fall Guys is still an enjoyable experience with nothing to lose.




I don't know who's reading this review, considering Fall Guys isn't on Steam anymore (owned by Epic), but I'll put it out anyway. (I am trying to review every game I have 100% achievements on)

I have owned this game since the "golden era" of the game, 2020. The first season was some of the most fun I have had online, although it did come with a $20 price tag. I had a lot of fun until I eventually quit around S4. Although I played it and kept it installed for the most part, I fully came back to the game during the Free To Play Update. It was a breath of fresh air for the seemingly abandoned game. 

Of course, being a free-to-play Epic Game, there is an "item shop" with cosmetics available. Don't worry; it is nothing but items for your character. In my opinion, the game doesn't try to push paying too much, and paying no money starts you off with the best experience.

The overall gameplay of Fall Guys is pure fun. It works well on KB+M and controller, and although there are some dud maps, for the most part, they are fun. It's not the most competitive game, so casual players will feel fine. 

In my opinion, this is a "better with friends" experience. It works okay when you are by yourself, but as a multiplayer game, playing duos or squads is great. There is also a map-maker, if that interests you, although it was a little underwhelming to me but very easy to learn and capable for most.

The biggest issue with Fall Guys is repetitiveness. This is especially clear when playing solo, but it is still apparent when playing Duos or Squads. After playing the same maps over and over again, it just feels bland, and unlike other free games, such as Fortnite, there isn't much that changes up the games. I suppose custom maps have somewhat fixed this issue, however. Along with that, the map rotation changes every season, which definitely brings my friends and I coming back to play.

Another issue is the fact that you have to own an Epic Account to play. This is definitely annoying, and the entire Epic Connection system is messy. If you don't want to be connected to Epic, don't play this game. It doesn't ruin the game; it just leaves a bad taste in the mouths of me and many other people.

Overall, Fall Guys is a breath of fresh air from typical shooter games and the like. Although it isn't the best on its own, it shines with friends, as do many other F2P multiplayer games. With solid gameplay and only a few issues, Fall Guys is multiplayer done right, and for the price of free, it definitely should be a game you should check out on Epic.

Achievements: For the most part, the achievements in this game are easy, and the majority of them happen without even trying. Unfortunately, a few of the achievements are cosmetic-related. When I got these achievements, cosmetics were free, and you could buy them with kudos, an in-game currency earned by playing. Unfortunately, these achievements now are basically pay-to-get (I'm not sure if you could get these for free). The rarest and by far the trickiest achievement is Infallible, earned by winning five games in a row. My tip is to wait for an easy LTM where win chances are much higher, which is how I got it.

[h1] Video Games [/h1]
 
While Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout isn't nearly as popular as it was around the time it launched, it still remains a perfect video game for what it sets out to accomplish. Its presentation, gameplay, low skill floor and price tag make it accessible to anyone who'd want to give it a try. If you're looking for something refreshing to play with a group of friends, even those who might not be big on video games, then look no further. 

Gameplay-wise, it is the best Wipeout or Ninja Warrior game (n?)ever made. You know, those shows where people have to beat an obstacle course in order to win the prize money? Here it‚Äôs a bit different, with up to 60 players thrown into a match, consisting of several rounds. At the end of every round, those who fail to complete the objective in time are eliminated. Not every round is an obstacle course however, but can be anything from a vast plethora of minigames spread into six different categories. 

For example, Race rounds will always task you with reaching the finish line of the course before a certain number of players manage to. Survival rounds will require you to not get eliminated before a certain number of players does, or a timer runs out. These are then further differentiated by themes and obstacles. One Survival round might have you balance atop of an ever-moving platform, dodging projectiles launched at you, while another will place you in an arena with three giant Rhinos attempting to knock you out. Team rounds, which require you to work with random players towards a common goal to prevent your entire team from being eliminated are all about scoring points, but can either be a game of basketball, football (the soccer kind) or collecting as high of a number of eggs as possible. 

In the main game mode, a match must always start with a Race and end with a Finale ‚Äì the most suspenseful, final round of the match, usually a Race that only one player can win or a Survival round that keeps going until the last man standing. Other game modes, both fixed and rotating, focus on specific categories or levels themselves. There are also custom matches you can make for you and your friends.

https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=2618963922

Even if all rounds across a category follow a certain pattern, none ultimately feel the same. Additional obstacles will sometimes appear on maps they were previously absent from, so the game can still throw you a curveball even when you think you have them all memorised. 

Still, some are clearly better designed than others. Door Dash, a Race round, is a course consisting entirely out of doors. Some of these are openable, while the others aren‚Äôt ‚Äì with there being no way of telling between the two until you try going through them. It almost completely eradicates the momentum of the match. If you go for an unlocked door consistently enough, you‚Äôll qualify. If you don‚Äôt, tough luck. Other levels that solely consist of multitudes of the same obstacle have a similar effect, though none are as bad as Door Dash.

https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=2618967222

The controls are quite tight due to how limited they are. You can jump, grab (players, ledges, objects and some objectives) and dive, so the game requires a total of three buttons to play ‚Äì excluding movement. A controller is ideal, but the keyboard and mouse perform almost just as well.

Progression feels good, but it could be better. Winning a round will net you a Crown, the game‚Äôs ‚Äô‚Äôpremium‚Äô‚Äô currency awarded solely through wins or milestones in the current Season‚Äôs battle pass-like progression, called Fame levels ‚Äì limited to 50 per Season and increased by XP, which is awarded for each match you play. Each Crown you acquire also increases your overall player rank, which awards you cosmetics upon leveling up and is separate from your Fame level. 

Besides Crowns, there are Kudos, a second currency awarded at certain Fame levels, as well as upon completion of a match regardless of whether you won or not. Kudos can also be purchased through microtransactions, in bundles as costly as $50, more than twice the game‚Äôs price. While the game isn‚Äôt by any means stingy with its rewards, the progression does feel a bit staggered and the inclusion of microtransactions can‚Äôt help but make me think of some marketing analyst or currency designer figuring out how to optimize it best to incentivise a purchase. Even when they aren‚Äôt intrusive, they‚Äôre there for a reason.

Your rewards can be spent in the store for cosmetic items. Some cost Kudos, some cost Crowns. There‚Äôs a fixed number of items that can be displayed in the store at a time and they reset once a day. Simple as. Customization options for your Fall Guy are quite varied and some visually striking combinations are possible, even without playing much.

Visually, the game is a colorful joy to look at, with the audio making it all the more appealing. The Fall Guys make cute ‚Äô‚Äôoofs‚Äú and other sounds when they collide with each other, and scream of excitement when an obstacle launches them into the air ‚Äì all of it heightened by a groovy, bass driven soundtrack. It just oozes fun.

https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=2618970077

Performance wise, the game ran great on max settings, at a steady 60 FPS. However, the animation LOD distance wasn‚Äôt that great, as players and obstacles further away would be running at a notably lower framerate. I don‚Äôt know if this is simply the way the game‚Äôs optimised, or something affected by the limitations of my specs. Weirdly enough, the game would sometimes drop down to 30 FPS while waiting in the lobby or the post-match recap.
 
Reviewed on the following system:

[table][tr][td]CPU [/td][td]AMD Ryzen 5 3600 3.6GHz[/td][/tr][tr][td]GPU[/td][td]GeForce GTX 1050Ti[/td][/tr][tr][td]RAM [/td][td]16GB[/td][/tr][/table]

While the game‚Äôs current player numbers are a far cry from what it once had, it still maintains a healthy population, both on Steam and outside of it, thanks to cross-play. I wholeheartedly hope that Mediatonic can keep Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout in such a state, as it‚Äôs a fun game that truly anyone can play. Even if you don‚Äôt end up winning, the little animation your Fall Guy does during the post-match summary shows that he‚Äôs had a lot of fun even participating, just as you will. Here‚Äôs to hoping it can keep going strong in the years to come, at least as long until there‚Äôs a worthy successor.

Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout is a multiplayer party game where you compete against 59 other people and try to beat sets of minigames only to be thrown into a finale and win it all. 

You can jump, dive or grab other people to mess with them or ensure your survival.

Minigames range from races, team games, survival rounds, scoring points to qualify.

The game works in seasons, each season the game gets a new theme, new maps and costumes/cosmetics. As you play you earn money that can be spend on cosmetics or emotes in the shop and you also earn experience which fills up your season pass which rewards you with something each level all the way to 50.

Months after release, the game recieved Squads ( que up with 3/2 or just one other friend and compete against teams of others), events where you have to complete tasks to get sets of points for special cosmetics ( like Ratchet and Clank costumes ) and special game modes that where you play the same map over and over until you reach the finale and try to win.

The big issue I personally have with the game is the content loop and while I understand that demanding updates frequently is not realistic, the way this game does it just isnt for me anymore. The experience for me was like this:

1. New season comes out. Play it as much as possible because its gone in 14 days. ( new levels always have a timer and then they get added into all the gamemodes, they are not gone forever but you cant specifically que them just like you would at the start of a season, why is that the case I dont know, it doesnt make sense at all since seasons last months )

2. Get burned out because you played too much. ( might aswell no life first few days if the new season only game mode is leaving soon )

3. Take a break because you are not having fun.

4. Come back near the end of a season, grind again to finish the season pass for cosmetics, quit again because the grind makes you dislike the game.

5. Repeat step 1

During season 4 I told myself that I dont really like this loop im kinda stuck in but I figured since it has been a bit early to judge the game Ill just keep playing and hopefully the game gets better in the future.

I wish I knew why are the developers alergic to reworking past minigames to make them more random instead of "if I always go like this I never get hit" bs. Its a bad way to describe it so lets just say if your strategy works once it will always work but it really shouldnt.

I also dont get why the season pass is only up to level 50. Once you reach it, there is nothing else to get, no extra levels that reward other ingame currencies, nothing. 

And finally the shop size stays the same despite adding tons and tons of new cosmetics every season, lets keep the shop nice and small to force players to check every day just incase there is something they want. Its stupid, the size should have been increased months ago.

And here we are over a year later and the game still does the same things over and over again and I cant lie to myself anymore and pretend that things will get better in the future. They cleary wont and its a damn shame.

"Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout," developed by Mediatonic, burst onto the gaming scene in 2020, captivating players with its delightful blend of whimsy, competition, and slapstick chaos. This multiplayer battle royale game takes a refreshing departure from the conventional with its colorful aesthetics, accessible gameplay, and a charmingly frenetic atmosphere that turns every match into a rollercoaster of laughs and surprises.

The visual design of "Fall Guys" is an instant eye-catcher. The bean-shaped characters, each sporting a variety of costumes, bounce, tumble, and somersault through a series of obstacle courses and challenges. The vibrant, candy-colored world creates a lively and inviting environment that is both charming and disarming.

At the heart of the gameplay is the chaotic journey through obstacle courses and team-based challenges, with up to 60 players contending to be the last bean standing. The simplicity of the controls‚Äîrunning, jumping, grabbing‚Äîmakes "Fall Guys" accessible to players of all ages, while the unpredictability of each round keeps the experience fresh and entertaining.

The brilliance of "Fall Guys" lies in its unpredictability and sheer fun factor. Whether navigating spinning platforms, dodging giant fruit, or jostling with other players to secure a coveted position, every moment is a mix of skill, luck, and delightful absurdity. The variety of courses and challenges ensures that no two rounds are alike, providing a dynamic and ever-evolving experience.

The collaborative and competitive nature of team challenges adds a layer of strategy and camaraderie. Whether working together to achieve a collective goal or sabotaging opponents to secure an individual victory, the team dynamics contribute to the social and unpredictable nature of the game.

The game's progression system, while somewhat limited in its early iterations, has been enhanced through updates. The addition of new costumes, emotes, and other customization options provides a sense of progression and personalization, encouraging players to keep diving into the vibrant world of "Fall Guys."

The occasional drawbacks include server issues, especially during peak times, which can result in frustrating connection problems. However, the developers have been responsive to these challenges, continuously working to improve server stability and overall player experience.

In conclusion, "Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout" is a delightful and whimsical triumph in the world of multiplayer gaming. Its accessible gameplay, unpredictable challenges, and charming visuals make it a standout title for casual and competitive players alike. While server issues have been a temporary hiccup, the ongoing support and updates from Mediatonic demonstrate a commitment to refining and expanding the game. "Fall Guys" has succeeded in creating a virtual playground where laughter, competition, and the quest for a crown collide, offering an endearing and chaotic experience that has left players falling for the charm of those adorable, bumbling beans.

This is a good game and I will show you my opinion of this great game:
The Good: The physics are really good, the graphics are nice, and the movement is so easy. The room searching is quick and the online gameplay is great compared to other online games. There are lots and lots of gamemodes, maps, costumes, events, and lots more that make the game great. There's even a thing where you can make your own level!

The Bad: For some people, there is this weird thing where the player gets a black screen for a long time when they press play, and have to wait for like 3 minutes before they can accualy play. However, there are many videos on how to fix this. Another thing is that sometimes you dive into one of those tilting platforms, and then you just glitch through the ground of the platform. Then another really frustrating thing is that for some reason, usually in the FINAL round, all the other players seem to be AFK and just stand motionless at spawn, but you can still move. Yeah that may seem nice, but that's a really annoying error. For example, a player gets that error, gets really close to the crown and BOOM!!! AN ERROR HAS ECCOURED screen pops up and the player has one choic. Can you guess what that is? To leave the server. Ouch!

The Ugly: If you are far away from a fall guy and they are moving, they tent to lag discustingly compared to the other great graphics in the game.

Personaly, I have never got one of the errors and I just love the game. I hope you trust my feedback and I hope you enjoy FALL GUYS!

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.
After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô• minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

Fall Guys, one of the surprise hits of 2020, is an innovative take on the battle royale genre and has become my favourite online game!

Pros:
[list]
    [*] A lot of customization options available
    [*] Regional servers are available with almost no downtime
    [*] Can play in short intervals
    [*] In-game music is fantastic
[/list]
Cons:
[list]
    [*] Team games are part luck and part skill-based
    [*] Item shop induces FOMO
[/list]

All in all, I would definitely recommend playing this game.

Update in 2021: Still going strong with all the updates like crown rank, squad mode, different game modes, live events, cross-play, custom shows, daily challenges, report system, level variations, news feed, crown shards, fall feed, and many collab costumes.

Update in 2022: F2P, delisted from steam, show bucks currency, overhauled shop, voice chat, full cross platform, themed shows, and expanded fame pass.

Update in 2023: Mainly creative mode is new. Although I mostly play on my ps5 now, hopefully one day I'll cross 1000 hours of gameplay on pc.

The game is really fun. It's brain dead, and if you like 3D platformers you'll love this. I bought this game originally, but then EPIC took it over and is now charging people for the really unique cosmetics with an in game currency called "show bucks." That's a huge downer, but it doesn't take away from the gameplay, and it's certainly not pay to win. If you don't buy the "season" passes, you also won't be able to unlock certain things while you level up. I refuse to buy anything extra as I feel that is just lighting my money on fire. You can still get the in game currency for free (both kudos and star bucks) but at a much, much slower pace, and it will take forever to unlock any of the more unique cosmetics without paying. I don't really care about the cosmetics and generally use this game to veg out after work or kill some time. You can still get patterns and other less unique cosmetics by using the other in game currency called "kudos." Consider the game beaten when you get your first solo crown in my opinion. 9/10.

This game was a lot of fun for the good-natured goofiness of just running around and being silly little beans. But as a collector, the crown-exclusives took away that kind of enjoyment and instead of motivating me to play more, had me clock in less. Having to place 1st and within a season's period of limited availability made it a lot less enticing to play. Devs could've easily fixed this by just making crown exclusive items exchangeable for a large amount of points, but they didn't. Having to compete with more than fun in mind and was a huge turn-off from continuing to play the game. If this was meant to keep people playing, well it didn't. Could've easily done the same thing and kept more casual players with the point implementation. There would also be a lot less trolling and in the earlier days, cheating, if crowns weren't such a highly valued currency.

[h2]Fall Guys: Where Jellybeans Dream of Victory![/h2]

Welcome to the wacky world of "Fall Guys," where the laws of physics and logic take a vacation, and jellybeans embark on the most chaotic obstacle courses ever devised. This game is so hilariously chaotic that even your grandma would don her jellybean costume and dive headfirst into the madness.

In "Fall Guys," you play as a plump, jiggly jellybean with a singular goal: be the last one standing in a series of absurd challenges. Whether it's navigating rolling fruit, surviving giant swinging pendulums, or racing up slippery slopes, you'll quickly realize that "graceful" isn't in your jellybean vocabulary.

The best part? You're competing against a bunch of other equally inept jellybeans. It's a laugh-out-loud battle royale where you'll trip, stumble, and occasionally achieve moments of heroic clumsiness. And when you fail, it's not a loss; it's just a funny accident waiting to be turned into a GIF for the internet to enjoy.

You'll soon discover that "Fall Guys" is a game of pure nonsense. Where else can you see a jellybean crowd cheering for a lone jellybean rolling a giant ball up a hill, only to have it roll back down and flatten everyone like pancakes? It's like a game show hosted by a bunch of caffeinated maniacs on a sugar rush.

Customizing your jellybean is a blast. Dress up as a pirate, a hot dog, or an astronaut, and strut your stuff on the catwalk - or, more accurately, the obstacle course. Winning crowns to unlock new outfits is almost as addictive as the gameplay itself. Who cares if you don't win the game? You've got the fashion game nailed!

But don't let the hilarious chaos fool you; "Fall Guys" can be surprisingly competitive. The struggle for that elusive crown can be intense, and you'll find yourself shouting at your screen in both joy and frustration. It's the only game where you can celebrate a victory by doing the chicken dance in a medieval knight costume.

In summary, "Fall Guys" is a belly laugh-inducing, physics-defying, and costume-customizing delight. It's the perfect game to play with friends, whether you're laughing at each other's failures or celebrating a well-deserved victory. Just remember: in "Fall Guys," the only thing more ridiculous than winning is losing. So dive in, laugh it off, and may your jellybean dreams of victory be as squishy as they are sweet!

The game has since been going downhill. I really must wonder at what point developers will learn to not let Epic Games buy them out, and I'm also wondering when people will stop giving money to a corporation that clearly hates them.

Thanks Epic Games, for ruining another good game.

[h1]Callow and Saccharine[/h1]

[i]There will be a TL;DR at the end[/i].

~

Fall Guys is built upon the foundation of a novel concept: 
Take the expensive idea of the Wipeout game show and make it accessible to all.
The execution is about as well as you might hope for, and it creates a certainly enjoyable initial experience as you tumble through increasingly impractical physical trials.

Fantastic presentation throughout - fantastic music and juicy audio enhance the otherwise plain aesthetic.
Simple controls - easy to read and grasp. Its not a bad game if you're new to interactive media itself. You could get your grandma to play this game and even she'd be able to wrap her mind around the controls in a short while.
A lot of hard work and effort is clear in the final product. It's visually polished and the moment-to-moment gameplay is smooth.

However, playing the game reminds me of cotton candy.
It is vaporous and passing; Fall Guys is a fading sugar high of empty calories that is bound to let you down in a hurry in spite of its profound efforts to grip you with its flavor.

The game is simply insubstantial.
There is a disturbing lack of dynamics in the game, which makes a benefactor out of young audiences and newcomers that might struggle - but ends up too shallow to be stimulating in the long run.
Muted - yet unsafe; the game is obviously aimed towards kids, but battle passes and paid cosmetics make it predatory in nature... you're going to want to keep any impressionable or wide eyed tyke away from playing this on their lonesome. it offers them little more than jingling keys anyhow.

There's also a fundamental problem in the game's basic feel - the texture of its engagement.
The better you are, the more trivial the victory. The worse you are, the more hopeless it might seem. Iv'e seen pro players waltz through matches without tripping or stumbling once to secure the gold medal - but I more often see wide swaths of players standing idly and waiting for their inevitable defeat, having accepted their inadequacy.
It's surprisingly easy to get discouraged when having a bad time, yet it's difficult to feel engaged when the match isn't a challenge. Chasing that narrow victory is passing and hollow - and just about never leaves you with any satisfaction.
Players will either feel like someone more experienced aced them, or that there's little competition.
There isn't much in between.

The game also has a disturbingly high amount of down-time with nothing to keep you engaged between the long periods of inactivity. It takes quite a bit to hop into a match, waiting to load into the match, waiting for the intro - then, when you're done with the level - waiting for all of the slowpokes to catch up, then waiting for the outro, waiting for the next level. Rinse and repeat until you leave the game and have to wait through your awards ans a completely separate loading screen that kicks you to the main menu.

What's also disappointing is that Fall Guys has the same dopey target demographic as every new game:
Wild and crazy cross-promotion cosmetics with kooky appeal and recognizable (and misplaced) brand recognition.
While the aesthetic of these crazy additions to the game fit with the title's over-the-top presentation of garish colors and gaudy cosmetics - the sad truth is that this demographic has been catered to by a myriad of Fortnite-chasers that want in on that corner of the market. In the end, Fall Guys doesn't feel special because this exact business tactic and cosmetic roll-out has been done a million times and notably better.

There are better party games, even for kids.
It has little to offer mature gamers and will spoil the appetites of younger audiences.

On the upside, it's a game that you can sit down and play with your young children.
On the downside, there are better games out there to engage them through and this one has a scummy predatory market.

I felt like I had experienced all that this game has to offer me by the second hour.
The rest of my playtime was me slowly realizing that this was all that Fall Guys has to offer.

~

[h2]TL;DR[/h2]
[b]4/10[/b].
Fall Guys is a [b]Below Average[/b] game.
While inoffensive and safe enough, it does little to stand out on its own.
While I didn't hate the game, it simply failed to impress with its humble selection of itinerant tastes. 
It's a novel concept, but it only has one good idea that fizzles quickly.
While not bad, it is all fluff and no substance. There are simply better experiences out there.
Plays smoothly on Steam Deck with basic settings, can easily switch back and forth to PC as well.

Playing Fall Guys in prison was a surreal experience that began with a mix of scepticism and intrigue. I found myself in a situation I never could have imagined, serving time for a mistake I deeply regretted. In the confines of the prison's recreation room, a fellow inmate had managed to smuggle in a gaming console, and it wasn't long before word got out about this quirky and entertaining game called Fall Guys.

The moment I picked up the controller, it was like a burst of colourful, chaotic energy entered my life. In the game's whimsical world, I became a jellybean-like contestant, navigating through a series of obstacle courses, racing against fellow inmates, and forming alliances as we aimed for victory. Fall Guys became an unexpected source of laughter and camaraderie, momentarily easing the tension that permeated our daily lives.

As days turned into weeks and seasons of Fall Guys came and went, our prison crew transformed into a formidable squad. We cheered each other on and shared the joy of both victories and defeats. In the midst of adversity, this game brought us moments of pure joy and friendship.

Playing Fall Guys in prison reminded me that even in the most challenging circumstances, there can be moments of light and connection. It was a reminder that, no matter where you are, the bonds formed through shared experiences can transcend the boundaries of reality and provide a glimmer of hope in the most unlikely places.

I think I should've written a review for this game shortly after playing this game, but I didn't bother. But hey, it's never too late to review! 

Anyway, I bought Fall Guys when it's was still in its paid access stage. It was around December 2020. I was really blown away with the game at the time. It was definitely worth the ¬£16 that I had paid for it. There was so much and you nearly never got bored of the game! It kept me entertained for hours on end. 

Anyway, when Epic Games acquired Fall Guys, they treated it like it was a new game. I missed out on the first season as you then had to sign up for an Epic account, which I was not interested in at the time. I eventually gave in and did though just so that I could play again, and I wasn't all that impressed with the changes. 

The new Fall Guys looked completely different, as it had kind of become a Fornite type system: you had to pay for everything within the game, and you still do! It makes sense considering  that the game was made free. 

So, overall, I would still say that the playing experience is still really good! It's just the in games purchases that are a problem now. But I would definitely recommend this game to people who like competitive types of games.

This game continues to be just bad. You play it more thinking, "If I just get a little better with the mechanics, then I will win more and have more fun." But no. Getting better barely improves your odds, because a large majority of the game's physics and outcomes come down to sheer luck. That's the problem with this game: There's not enough opportunity to really excel in many aspects of gameplay, and your character, being a fat slob, does not obey you. The game could be so much more, but it isn't. Roll the die and see if the odds are ever in your favor this time. Most people are going to lose, sure, but you want to lose for the right reasons, because you were outskilled or out-strategized, because your teamwork was of a lower quality.

Also their most fun mini-games are played the least, like sportsball (what I call soccer), volleyball (is that still a thing?), and snowball roll, and the generic games get annoying. Only if you make it to the latter stages do you get to play these more fun mini-games.

Things to know:
- I'm rating Fall Guys in two ways: before and after New Season 1.
- Most of the pro's are aimed at everything before New Season 1.
- A lot of the con's are aimed at everything after New Season 1.
- I have owned and played the game since the original Season 1.
- I have played every single season and every minigame, with the exception of any I might've accidentally missed in New Season 4.
- I have all the achievements.


Pros:
- Fun party game with friends.
- I love that you can make private lobbies, even if you need a bunch of people to do so
- Even if you don't have friends who own the game and you're riding solo, this is still pretty fun on your own.
- Crowns were an amazing way to flex your experience in the game and force players to "git gud" for the cool skins.
- The physics and atmosphere are hilarious, I have plenty of moments with friends when the goofy physics have made for some memorable games.
- Thank you Mediatonic for not giving us stupid edgy/anime skins 24/7 and leaning into the goofy side of the game, TAKE NOTES FORTNITE >:(


Cons:
- This game's identity was completely lost once the new Season 1 started and basically turned into Fortnite: Bean Edition.
- All Steam Users have effectively been screwed and are forced to make an Epic Games account to play, why is this even needed?
- Hope you got this game during new Season 1 and didn't pay for this game prior, otherwise you aren't getting a refund or any worth while items in its place.
- Removing crowns as a currency makes the replay value diminish greatly.
- Back in the day, I remember buying the fall guys pass during Season 2 for extra rewards, then never again. Now I gotta buy a new one every season? Thanks, I was really looking for a new outlet to waste money for.
- Compared to Season 6, all the new seasons feel like you have to grind for rewards.
- This company had the audacity to call New Season 4, "Creative Construction" when they literally reused the Kraken Slam OST from New Season 3 as the main theme. Luckily they made a unique OST for New Season 4 now, but I'm not overlooking that level of laziness from a company that is now consider an AAA Studio.

Summary: As of now, I don't think Fall Guys is worth it at all unless you are fine with being a free to play. If I was rating Fall Guys prior to New Season 1, I'd give it a 9.1/10 with the only downside being the physics in the game can cause you to lose games and some minigames are a bit unbalanced.

As of New Season 1 prior, the gameplay is still fine, it just feels like the entire identity of Fall Guys is lost entirely, because it just feels like Fortnite now. No more crowns, unnecessary purchases, and it doesn't feel fun anymore. Honestly, I give it a 4.7/10 thanks to the loss of identity, feeling like a clone of Fortnite, and a complete disregard for all platforms who play the game.

I am a 75 yo grandfather, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single grandfather to my grandson, who is 14 now. My grandson got this game for Christmas in 2021 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my grandson, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So i decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and world and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my grandson for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my grandson since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my grandson closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my grandson many happy memories.

Probably one of the best party games on the market. In any case for me it's the best on steam with Tower Unite, in a style certainly more childish than the latter but just as fun. Then frankly combining Party Game and Battle Royale with too cute little guys is not the class?
Children and adults will be able to meet without any worries in complete safety given the absence of IG chat. We will therefore avoid any toxicity to leave fun and frustration alone in control.

You can of course play it with your friends but in a limit of 4 players max unfortunately.

We will also note a small lack of content, 25 maps of course but on which they quickly went around (Only 4 for the final) I even find that there are several that clearly lack interest and fun.
From what I currently know there will be a rotation with new maps every 2 and a half months or so.

Like Rocket League, you have access to a kind of battle pass to level up and earn items (Costume, IG Currency, Crown, Colors etc.). For now it's free so I hope it stays that way.

Otherwise the game itself is super fun, colorful and refreshing. The only thing we will have to watch now will be the player base which will determine whether or not the game will hold up in the long term or if it will have to be free to play to get there. 60 people to bring together each time is still not nothing and in a few weeks / months it could be more complicated.. Wait & See.

As usual a little thank you to the Mediatonic team and to Devolver for their fun and original games ‚ô•

Title: Hilariously Fun, But Developers Dropped the Ball

Rating: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ

Fall Guys is an absolute riot and has provided me and my friends with 41 hours of pure laughter and chaos. It's the perfect game to play with a group, and its whimsical graphics and absurd challenges make for a genuinely enjoyable experience. It's a party game that never fails to deliver on the promise of fun times and uncontrollable fits of giggles.

However, my enthusiasm for Fall Guys is dampened by my strong dislike for the developers' decision to remove the game from sale in Russia. Seriously, what were they thinking? It's like they took a page out of a comedy playbook, aiming for a punchline that nobody found funny. Denying an entire country the chance to join in on the fun is a baffling move that has left me scratching my head in disbelief.

While I can't deny the sheer enjoyment I've had with Fall Guys, I can't help but feel frustrated and disappointed by the developers' poor judgment. It's like they've set up the most entertaining party ever and then locked the door on some of the guests for no apparent reason. It's a misstep that casts a shadow over an otherwise fantastic game.

So, despite my reservations about the developers' baffling choice, I have to admit that Fall Guys is still a must-play game if you're lucky enough to have access to it. The laughs, the challenges, and the ridiculousness of it all are enough to make it a standout in the party game genre. Just be prepared to shake your head at the developers' puzzling antics while you're at it.

Someone mentioned Fall Guys in a discord call last night and I thought I'd jump back in and play again for a bit. When I first played in 2021, I adored this game for a multitude of reasons, but the main one was that it was a battle royale game I could really enjoy playing. I tend to prefer platformers over shooters, so this game ticked that box immediately, but what really made it for me was it's cartoony art style and fun level design.

This was completely absent when I jumped back in.

The new, community-made levels that pop up in the show selector have no visual flair whatsoever; the same backgrounds, building parts and in some cases, stage designs or obstacles. This is no fault of the community itself, mind you, but a complete lack of any option to make them such from the dev team. Feels like Super Mario Maker on Wii U where they failed to give you some basic features or designs if that makes sense, and as a result the levels feel same-y. What's more, the maximum amount of players that can be in a game has been lowered from 60 to 40, which honestly removes some of the chaotic mad rush caused by an enormous mob of players trying to reach the end of the stage. 

There also doesn't appear to be any new dev-created stages since I last played, it's the same levels that I played multiple times, which you can only enjoy so much before it becomes tiresome. Combining them with the community levels only exacerbates the problem. I got bored of playing pretty quickly, which is a real shame because I know how much fun Fall Guys is from a conceptual gameplay standpoint, which was nailed in 2021. For whatever reason, the devs have taken a complete step back, and have given the community very little to work with. I don't think I'll be coming back to play again unless future updates look genuinely impressive and address the issues, and even though it's free to play now, I personally wouldn't recommend picking it up until then either. Not that you can on Steam anyway, considering that Devolver decided to make it exclusive to Epic.

Nearly 1,600 hours on record and I'll continue to play it, but I can't recommend it. Here's why:

The Fall Guys that launched and had 6 solid seasons is long gone. Oh how I long for the days of rounds with 60 Beans and all those classic maps that are now "vaulted". That's right, most of the maps you enjoyed which were huge hits through the first 6 seasons are long gone. Why? No idea. My guess is they had some kind of internal vote or a closed community vote and everyone who sucks at the game voted the more challenging maps, you know, the fun ones, out. This game caters to a younger generation so I guess I shouldn't be surprised that the larger, challenging maps are gone. God forbid kids have to work at something and get good at it and earn a prize. Now you get shards for doing nothing at all. Any challenge that remained up until the overhaul is long gone unless you like community maps made by people who are obsessed with making the most insanely difficult, virtually impossible maps to get through in the game. Most of the community maps are just frustrating junk that maybe a handful of psychos can get through and you'll only be competing with a few other people if you are lucky. The latest co-op maps are almost completely empty at this point. Enjoy playing a multiplayer game alone. Fun.

So what the hell happened to Fall Guys? Like every game that's been taken over by a large corporate entity, micro-transactions have all but ruined the experience. The quality of the game has taken a serious hit and for nearly 6 months before the complete overhaul, we were stuck playing maybe 7 or 8 of the most boring, tedious maps over and over and over because some super genius decided to vault all the good maps. You actually knew what map was coming all the time and it just became a nauseating nightmare slog to get a crown. It was pretty obvious at that point that whoever was running the show had money on the brain instead of keeping the game interesting and challenging.

Low and behold, the overhaul came and sure enough it's basically just a money grab at this point. It's transactions for skins and transactions for season passes. Most of the good, old school maps are vaulted. Remember that season, Satellite Scramble? I think maybe one of those maps survived and it's the lame finale. That season had amazing maps and they are all GONE. What was the point of even having that season? Winter Knockout? Medieval Knockout? All gone. At best you might get a finale or maybe a stupid jump through the hoops round.

One of the biggest thrills of Fall Guys was checking in every morning to see what skins were available in the hopes that you'd finally get a rare one you were looking for. And you needed a lot of Kudos to get those skins. Now Kudos is pretty much totally worthless unless you are interested in a lame pair of sunglasses or a belt for your Bean. Dumb. Now you can just buy whatever you want. There's no more thrill to collecting skins, at all. They're all on rotation and they can all be easily purchased. In fact, they have to be purchased unless you want utter crap.

For me the biggest let down of all was vaulting the good maps in favor of easy junk to appease the toddlers who play the game for free. These are people who don't even support the community.

Creator Content is an okay addition and I've even made a few maps, but it's never going to make up for vaulting most of the good maps in the game. That was the dumbest decision they could have made. Also, whatever happened to 100 player rounds? Guess that was a lie. You don't even see 60 player rounds anymore. They've whittled it down to 30 or 40 at most if the server is even full.

The only redemption for this game is going to be bringing back the hundreds of classic maps that were vaulted and also bringing back some sort of opportunity to score good skins for Kudos. All those DLC skin packs? Bring them back in the old format of random tops and bottoms for huge amounts of Kudos.

As of right now, this game is in a death spiral for me, 1,600 hours in. Shame.

The game is a lot of fun for 2-10 hours or so, but gets really stale soon after.
It's biggest problem is the repetitive nature of the stages at the beginning.
A person can only have so much fun playing the same stage over and over again, while being showcased a variety of stages during the loading screen after every won round.
No stage is difficult enough to be deemed as a "progression reward" for playing.

E: The game is completely overrun by cheaters at this point.
There is absolutely no way of reporting anyone and the game devs don't seem to give a rat's ass about dealing with this issue.

The map rotation is terrible, team modes aren't fun at all, tail tag boils down to the last 5 seconds with an awful grab mechanic (the game favors people with high ping, so they can steal your tail without making any contact) and jinx is full of exploits that the devs don't seem to care about fixing (such as jumping out of map and out of reach of others, jumping onto an invisible platform, etc.)

Fall Guys burst onto the gaming scene with its delightful blend of whimsy, chaos, and addictive gameplay. This party game extravaganza offers a refreshing and lighthearted experience that appeals to players of all ages. From the moment you dive into the vibrant and colorful world of Fall Guys, you'll find yourself immersed in a joyous and hilarious adventure.

One of the standout features of Fall Guys is its unique take on the battle royale genre. Rather than intense firefights, the game replaces bullets and violence with an assortment of fun-filled obstacle courses and wacky challenges. As a jellybean-like character, you'll navigate a series of increasingly outrageous and unpredictable levels, competing against other players to be the last one standing. The gameplay is fast-paced and addictive, as you find yourself constantly laughing, cheering, and sometimes even screaming with delight as you dash, jump, and tumble your way through each zany obstacle.

Fall Guys excels in its accessibility and pick-up-and-play nature. The controls are simple and intuitive, making it easy for players of all skill levels to jump in and start having fun right away. The game's emphasis on lighthearted and goofy gameplay fosters an inclusive and welcoming environment, perfect for both casual gamers and seasoned players looking for a break from more intense titles.

Visually, Fall Guys is a treat for the eyes. The whimsical and vibrant art style, coupled with adorable character designs, creates a world that is bursting with charm and personality. Each level is meticulously crafted with colorful and imaginative themes, from towering obstacle courses to bouncing platforms and slippery slides. The attention to detail in the visual design adds an extra layer of immersion, making each level feel like a playful adventure.

One of the standout aspects of Fall Guys is its multiplayer experience. Whether you're playing with friends in a party or joining random players online, the game's multiplayer mode is a chaotic blast. The combination of teamwork, competition, and sheer randomness creates moments of both camaraderie and hilarity. Collaborating or competing with other players to reach the finish line or snatch victory in a team-based challenge adds an exciting social element to the gameplay.

It's worth mentioning that Fall Guys' reliance on server stability has caused occasional issues, including connection problems and matchmaking delays. However, the developers have shown dedication in addressing these concerns and working towards a smoother experience.

In conclusion, Fall Guys is an absolute delight of a game, offering an irresistibly charming and uproarious multiplayer experience. Its whimsical visuals, accessible gameplay, and infectious sense of fun make it a standout title for parties or casual play. Fall Guys is a testament to the power of a lighthearted approach to gaming, creating moments of laughter and joy that are truly infectious. So grab your friends, get ready to stumble, and prepare for a hilarious adventure that will keep you entertained for hours on end.

Epic Games had to ruin everything. Removed the game from Steam, made it free and added microtransactions. Players that bought the game received awful rewards for buying it after it got free to play, and all the crowns we earned were turned into Kudos, a currency that is now obsolete because Epic created their own currency, the Show Bucks. Gaming companies are greedy and will want more, and in the future things will be way worse. We really shouldn't accept these actions, but sadly I guess we're too late. Fall Guys was one of my favorite battle royale games when it originally released, I still enjoy playing it time to time. While when I originally played it it wasn't free, it was still worth the money.
Fall Guys is a battle royale platformer game where you try to be the last "guy" standing out of 100 players. There are a variety of game modes and maps, with many more coming in future updates. While not every game mode is stellar, the sheer variety of modes on display means that even if there are 1 or 2 that you dislike, there are still plenty more modes available. The graphics, controls, and vibe of the game are great, and helps it stand out in a sea of battle royale games.
The only complaint I truly have about this game is how long loading times can be. In between each game you'll be waiting for sometimes minutes for the next round to start. This causes for matches to take much longer than they should and also causes for awkward pacing in what should be a fast and snappy battle royale.
While there are in-app purchases and the like in this title, they are, just like Fornite, only skins, and do not actually impact the gameplay at all. If you want, you don't have to spend a dime on this game and still get the full experience.
Overall, while I do have a few issues with Fall Guys, I would still recommend downloading it on the Epic Games Store to at least try it out. It is free after all, so there's no harm in trying. While this game is definitely past its glory days, I still enjoyed my time with it and I still come back to it every so often.

Chocolate Chip Cookies:
1 cup butter, softened
1 cup white sugar
1 cup packed brown sugar
2 eggs
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
1 teaspoon baking soda
2 teaspoons hot water
¬Ω teaspoon salt
3 cups all-purpose flour
2 cups semisweet chocolate chips
1 cup chopped walnuts

Step 1
Preheat oven to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C).

Step 2
Cream together the butter, white sugar, and brown sugar until smooth. Beat in the eggs one at a time, then stir in the vanilla. Dissolve baking soda in hot water. Add to batter along with salt. Stir in flour, chocolate chips, and nuts. Drop by large spoonfuls onto ungreased pans.

Step 3
Bake for about 10 minutes in the preheated oven, or until edges are nicely browned.

[h1] Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout - A Whimsical Battle Royale Party Game [/h1]

Overall Rating: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ

Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout, developed by Mediatonic, is a delightful and whimsical battle royale party game that brings together elements of platforming, obstacle courses, and competitive multiplayer. With its colorful visuals, charming characters, and chaotic gameplay, Fall Guys offers a refreshing and entertaining experience for players of all ages.

Graphics: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ
Fall Guys features vibrant and colorful graphics that are both visually appealing and charming. The game's whimsical art style, cute character designs, and lively animations create a cheerful and inviting atmosphere. The environments, filled with imaginative obstacles and unique challenges, are well-designed and add to the overall fun and playful aesthetic.

Gameplay: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ
The gameplay of Fall Guys revolves around competing in a series of wacky and unpredictable challenges with a large group of players. From racing through obstacle-filled courses to team-based mini-games, each round presents a new and exciting challenge. The controls are simple and intuitive, making it accessible to both casual and experienced gamers. The chaotic nature of the gameplay, combined with the unpredictability of other players' actions, creates a thrilling and often hilarious experience.

Sound: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ
Fall Guys features a lively and upbeat soundtrack that matches the game's energetic and lighthearted tone. The background music enhances the fun and frantic atmosphere, while the sound effects add to the overall immersion. From the joyful cheers of the characters to the comical sounds of bouncing and falling, the audio elements contribute to the game's charm and entertainment value.

Multiplayer Experience: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ
Fall Guys shines in its multiplayer experience, allowing players to compete against others from around the world in both competitive and cooperative challenges. The game supports both local and online multiplayer, fostering a sense of camaraderie and competition among friends. The inclusion of party modes and the ability to form teams adds another layer of enjoyment, making it an excellent choice for social gatherings or online play with friends.

Replayability: ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÖ‚òÜ
Fall Guys offers high replayability, thanks to its ever-changing selection of courses and challenges. Each match presents a different combination of rounds, ensuring that no two games are the same. The addictive nature of trying to secure a victory and the desire to unlock new cosmetic items and outfits provide further incentive for repeated play.

Conclusion:
Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout is a whimsical and entertaining battle royale party game that is sure to put a smile on your face. With its charming visuals, chaotic gameplay, and multiplayer fun, it offers an enjoyable and lighthearted gaming experience. Whether you're competing for the crown or laughing with friends, Fall Guys is a delightful addition to any gaming library.

Update: Nothing was ever fixed. Additionally, you spend the majority of your time loading, watching the map intro videos and watching beans fall off the board than you actually play the game. There is no excuse to spend this much time at these sections. 

In theory, I really like this game but the developers do not seem interested in fixing the core issues. 

If you can look past these, you'll have a fun time as there are many excellent stages so I recommend it to most casual players but I can't recommend it to someone who wants to sink hours into the game without these being fixed. These issues make the game too frustrating to play for me now.

Fall Guys has some excellent stages thanks to some talented people over at Mediatonic, the costumes are usually well designed, the price provides incredible value, the battle pass system format is second to none and they have an engaged community / social media team. They just seem to be lacking developers to help them fix the main issues.

Core Issues: 
- Server Desynchronization. The game has been out for a while now and it's becoming clear that this is not going to be fixed. What does this mean? Well, let's say you're in a Hex-A-Gone final round, there will be some people who are jumping on non-existent tiles that you already used from your perspective. It could also mean someone is behind you in a Fall Mountain final but they manage to grab the crown on Fall Mountain as they are actually ahead of you. Originally, I thought this was a heavy server load thing but as player population has continued to drop, there hasn't been much improvement. 

- Character Stability. Your character will fall over for no reason. Season 1 felt (mostly) fine. It got worse in Season 2 and it doesn't feel much better in Season 3. Sometimes, you fall on a Jump Showdown final due to this stability (even when you are not standing on the crack) and you will lose as your character decides to ragdoll randomly. Plus, ragdoll physics don't provide any value and the amount of time it takes to get back up can also be nearly random. 

- Character Collision. This goes hand in hand with stability. The number of players means that character collision shouldn't be this aggressive. It also feels like complete RNG whether bumping someone will push you off something or do nothing at all. You could be happily jumping near someone on a Jump Showdown final, you two bump each other midair but only one of you falls down while one of you is unharmed - despite jumping at the same time. The little beans just aren't stable enough to have this sort of collision in the game. It is far too much of a RNG element. 

- Wasted Time (loading, round animations, matchmaking). These all take way longer than they need to. You should avoid this game if you have limited time to play when you're gaming. You start out with some of the slowest matchmaking that I've ever seen for a game that has a decent player population (10000+ average players online) to find just 56-59 others (average, 43 seconds). When the game decides to find people, we then watch the scrolling screen of rounds to select from and wait for the game to pick one (on average, 20 seconds) (here, it should be loading the selected round in the background during this animation but seemingly, it does not). Next, we sit at "Waiting for Players" to load the chosen round (on average, 10 seconds) (we shouldn't wait here if it was loading it in the background during selection. These 10 seconds could be caused by players on HDDs, those with poor connections or a server-side issue). Now, when the round finally loads, it isn't time to play yet - it is time to watch a needless stage cinematic. The game then goes to a 3-2-1 countdown after the cinematic to begin. When the round is over, we watch the "Round Over" animation come up on the screen followed by players that lost drop off of a board (from the time you see the "Round Over", including the watching of the players fall off the board and ending with the next stage selection starting - on average 21 seconds) (again during this time, in the background, we could select and load the next stage but the developers don't seem to do this). You now proceed to repeat the process to select a stage, load the stage and watch the next cinematic before getting to play the next round. This adds up to 1.5 minutes or so including matchmaking. It's all far too long for a game of minigames in the age of NVMe drives and 1Gbit down/up connections.

- As a whole, the game is catering to a less skilled audience with Season 3. The modes were traditionally 50% skill and 50% luck (which was already too high for luck). The scales feel they've tipped in the luck direction even more with some of these new stages. 

- The new stages are far weaker than Season 1 and 2. Big Fans, Knights Fever are examples of stages to strive for. The Season 3 race even has advantageous spawn positions instead of being balanced (Freezy Peak). The game has fun, skill focused stages where you can learn the tricks and timings of the stage to improve. However, for each good stage, there is round where it can just come down to luck. Unfortunately, the game seems to be trending in the latter direction.

- The new Season 3 finals are far worse. Hex-A-Gone and Jump Showdown are still the best finals but Thin Ice is so common now. Fall Mountain could be good with bugfixes and lowering the maximum player count.

When Fall Guys launched, just a few months after the world shut down, it was right on track to be a perfect game. It brought friends together in a tough time with an engaging and undeniably goofy experience that just felt good to play. But with its refusal to create meaningful variety or adequately reward its playerbase for sticking around, the game just makes me sad imagining what could have been. Despite the promise of its premise, no opportunity for fun goes unignored.

Part 1 - The Fall

This is a game about falling over. It's simple, it's stupid, and it's brilliant. I love seeing a new course and finding out the new ways it can cause the players, myself included, to land on their face as they contend with an unfamiliar challenge. But a course is only fresh for the first few days of its release, and the moment it's understood, onto the pile it goes. It's just one more line of obstacles to churn through, with no real challenge left to offer you. You've stopped falling over.

When variety dies, fun dies with it. I'm not just talking about a lack of new stages. The amount of individual courses is perfectly serviceable as it is (the Vault notwithstanding), and it would be foolish to ask that the developers just keep churning out new and unique maps. What's missing is a way of shaking up the maps we already have. Once upon a time, some effort was made in that regard. Some stages have sections in which the typical obstacles can be randomly swapped out for different ones, or a wildly-swinging hammer may appear in select areas where it can knock a skilled player toward victory. These instances, however fun, are rare, and the developers appear unwilling to add more; this leaves an enormous chunk of levels completely static in their function. What's more, any effort put into these additions does add unfamiliarity to a level, but only for so long. At some point, you've just seen it all. But variety can itself be expressed in a variety of ways, and by their combination, we can multiply the level possibilities for very little additional effort. More possibilities to confuse the player, to get them to fall over.

My preferred solution is random stage modifiers. Give any course a chance to inflict a gameplay-altering effect that challenges the player to rethink a familiar course. I could list off modifiers all day, but here's a small taste:

Dizzy - Reversed controls!
Flightless - Jumping disabled! You can still dive.
Slippery - Ice physics!
Leaping - Jump is twice as high!
Startling - Grabbing another player causes them to jump!
Ghostly - Players do not collide! You can still grab.
Fishy - Run speed greatly reduced! Use dives to move quickly.
Wild - Several Rhinos are placed randomly on the course!
Tiring - Jumping has a 3-second cooldown.
Xtreme - No respawns, only elimination!

By no means is it one-size-fits-all, as not every stage can be completed with every modifier, but it would exponentially increase the total number of unique level combinations and ensure that even an experienced player would need to stop and think about what they're doing instead of always following the same practiced line that gets them to the end the quickest. They will approach with caution, they will be confused, and they will fall over. And falling over is the fun part.

Part 2 - The Guys

The bean-shaped playable characters in Fall Guys, are, by their design, nothing. When you boot up the game for the first time, you are given a naked pink Nothing Man to play as, which seems perfectly appropriate for the kind of game you're playing. After all, playing the game is half the fun, the other is how the game plans to reward you! "Great," you say, "I can't wait to unlock some outfits so I can stop being so nothing!". And you're half-right in your assessment: You will find outfits, but you will never stop being nothing.

With no intention to spend money on this free-to-play game, and certainly not the 8-or-so dollars the game expects for any of its premium outfit packages, your options may seem limited. By slowly accruing Kudos over days of play, however, you can expect to eventually afford a shiny pair of spiked wristbands and a neat sunhat to keep your Nothing Man looking stylish. If you wear the both of them together, maybe you can put together a pretty swanky new look for yourself. Oh, but what's this? Upper, Lower, Faceplate, Color, Pattern... Where's the Accessory tab? Surely you don't mean to tell me that if I wear these spiked wristbands, I can't wear anything else on my entire top half? And yet, this is exactly the case for every Kudos outfit: You may wear gloves, wristbands, glasses, or a hat. Individually, these costume pieces look great! But "individually" is all you get without Show Bucks, the freemium currency of which the game will toss you a few crumbs each month for dedicated play.

Aggressive monetization is to be expected from any free-to-play game, and Fall Guys is no exception. If you want your character to feel less naked, it's either play every day or cough up the dough. However you choose to acquire a nicer outfit for yourself, put it on and experience the freedom of your new polar bear costume! I just hope you don't mind the dead-eyed stare of your Nothing Man's faceplate looking back at you. Regardless of your outfit choice, it will have a gaping hole in the middle, ensuring the bland non-design of your playable character's face will always stab through the fun outfit and into your eyeballs. There's a Nothing Man inside that costume, the game says, don't forget about the Nothing Man. In the great paradox of Fall Guys' art design, it seems no price is high enough to hide the aspirin tablet with limbs they spent so long not designing.

If the character's face must be shown, why make it so devoid of identity? The treatment of the character as a strangely-shaped person, rather than a blank slate to be dressed over, is particularly problematic when the likeness of an actual human is hideously stretched over the cylindrical shape of the Nothing Man's body, complete with an artificial tan faceplate to remind you of the dark deed that has taken place. Wouldn't the task be better served by a character with a slight identity rather than none at all? Given the chance to step back to the beginning and present a different design, I would simply replace the slippery clumsy "people" with slippery clumsy penguins. An animal character has instant appeal no matter what outfit it's given to wear or what silly game show stunt it's asked to perform, which cannot be said for the Nothing Man. And if you still insist upon the face being seen, don't worry, at least penguins are cute.

Part 3 - The Ultimate Knockout

The switch from the pay-once model to free-to-play resulted in a change to the players' focus -- it has blurred to the point that it can be hard to see a reason to play at all. Before free-to-play, "premium" outfits were bought with 5 Crowns, one of which was awarded for each win. Crowns are no longer a spendable currency but instead go toward a linear and unchanging list of exclusive unlockable outfits for increasingly sweaty players to wear as status symbols (which, due to the aforementioned character customization, eliminates the ability to wear anything else). If you wish to wear the outfits you've purchased, whether with free or premium currency, winning has been effectively disincentivized.

Fall Guys is a game that deserved better than it got, and the window for any kind of real change closed years ago. When I turn back to take a look through that window, I see a better game. With every glacially slow season, it slips ever further into mediocrity, and I wish more and more to return to the first year of playing Fall Guys with friends before we discovered that occasionally being new and shiny was the best this game was going to get.
