Fall Guys is a refreshing take on battle royal games that manages to combine elements of platformers and obstacle course style games. The game's bright colours, silly sound effects, and playful animations make it a joy to look at and play.

Although it's easy to pick up and play, the gameplay can be quite challenging at times, especially as the rounds progress and the competition becomes tougher. While the game can be frustrating at times, especially when getting griefed by garbage players, its absolutely incredible when you win.

One of the strengths of Fall Guys is its variety of mini-games, which are all distinct and challenging in their own ways. From racing to the finish line to battling it out on seesaws and spinning platforms, each mini-game offers a different kind of challenge that keeps the gameplay fresh and engaging.

Overall, Fall Guys is a great game that is sure to provide hours of fun for players of all skill levels.

Fall Guys is like a game show on steroids, where the contestants are jelly beans with legs and the obstacles are designed by sadistic hamsters. It's a game that makes you feel like a kid again, except you're constantly losing to actual kids who seem to have way more coordination than you do. It's like being in a pinball machine, but instead of flippers, you're using your clumsy little bean arms to navigate through the chaos. The game is essentially a mix between Takeshi's Castle and a kindergarten playground, where the only thing you're really competing for is a fancy little crown that will make you feel like the king of all jelly beans. It's a game that makes you laugh until you cry, and then cry until you laugh again, all while trying to avoid giant balls and spinning discs.

It's so addictive that it's like a drug, except the only high you'll get is from winning a round and the low is from getting eliminated early. It's like playing a game of Russian Roulette, except instead of a gun, you're using your own incompetence and the bullets are brightly-colored bean-shaped obstacles.

Overall, Fall Guys is a hilarious, chaotic mess that will make you forget all about the real world for a while. It's a game that will have you screaming at your screen one moment, and then giggling uncontrollably the next. So, if you're looking for a game that will make you feel like a kid again, but with a dash of ridiculousness and a pinch of frustration, then Fall Guys is the game for you.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

6 tablespoons unsalted butter

1/2 cup white sugar

1/2 cup brown sugar

1/4 cup water

1/4 teaspoon cinnamon

1 pinch salt

5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced

1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).

Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.

Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.

Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.

Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.

Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

I have been dabbling with multiplayer games here and there, I played Fortnite, Apex Legends, Overwatch, Call of Duty, Halo Infinite, a single round of VALORANT before banishing it off of my PC, and unfortunately also ended up playing League of Legends, but the search for a game that was actually fun to play even at a low skill level had always been a Sisyphean task, and all of the less serious games have always been there for me, I always relapse into games like Knockout City and Omega Strikers because they are just fun, and will remain enjoyable due to their lack of competitiveness but insane amounts of replay value, and all of this is correct for the diamond in the rough known as Fall Guys, Fall guys is the perfect mix between goofiness and challenge where there is enough goofiness it doesn't feel like you are getting shat on by that one guy with better reaction time and aiming than you, but also enough challenge so that each level doesn't feel like a walk in the park, as you stumble over every other player trying to get to the end before getting disqualified or trying to stay alive until the timer ends is a really fun form of tension that I really enjoy when playing video games, but has only been implemented in story driven single-player games, not full on live service multiplayer games, but fall guys knew what it was doing for a very long time, even the developers themselves rent out inflatable obbies to race through in spirit of their amazing game, and with the new level editor, the replay value has skyrocketed, and Fall Guys has truly cemented itself as a Certified Hood Classic on my behalf.

I am a 45 yo father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single farther to my Son, who is 14 now. My son got this game for Christmas in 2022 from his uncle, so we installed it on his computer and he started playing. By the end of the week he had 24 hours on this game. This was horrible for me, as it was already hard for me to find ways to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching YouTube. So I decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, picked my character and started playing but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. This game reminded me that there's fun to be had in everything, and it has brought both me and my Son many happy memories.

Used to obsessed with Fall Guys since launch day due to it's concept and probably the game that influenced me into serious gaming (decided to upgrade to a gaming laptop just to play Fall Guys). But I gotta admit, ever since the Epic Games takeover, this game have gone downfall significantly.

From nice cosmetics that used to be obtainable by hard grinding the game (which honestly, feels more worth it), to be easily available just with some real money transaction. There's no real point really why I want to grind in this game other than completing the battle pass (which I don't even feel motivated to finish it nowadays).

Second of all, there's isn't really any big improvement to not just the game itself, but the developers as well. Lack of communications between players and developers, messy state of the game with all those hackers and delayed progress (it took almost a damn year from the Free-For-All update announcement for the developer to actually implement the level builder mode). Why even bother announcing it when you can't even manage to deliver it on time?

Heck, even the official community page (Twitter, Discord, etc) feels very different compared to those prior to the Epic Games takeover (OG players probably know what I'm talking about)

In summary, thanks Epic Games for ruining what I used to say, my favorite game of all time. You guys got the chance to revive this game from the "dead game" era prior to the Free-For-All update, but you guys jinxed it after that.

Orange Chicken and Chow Mein are two popular dishes in Chinese cuisine that are widely enjoyed by people all around the world. I recently had the opportunity to try these dishes, and here is my review of them.

Firstly, the Orange Chicken was absolutely delicious. The chicken was tender and juicy, and the orange sauce was tangy, sweet, and packed with flavor. The dish had the perfect balance of savory and sweet flavors, making it a truly satisfying meal. The chicken was also perfectly cooked, with a crispy exterior and a moist interior. Overall, I would highly recommend the Orange Chicken to anyone who loves Chinese cuisine.

Next, the Chow Mein was equally delicious. The noodles were cooked to perfection and had a wonderful texture that complemented the flavors of the dish. The vegetables in the Chow Mein were also fresh and flavorful, adding a nice crunch to each bite. The sauce was savory and delicious, tying all the flavors together perfectly. Overall, the Chow Mein was a great addition to the meal and provided a nice contrast to the sweetness of the Orange Chicken.

In conclusion, the Orange Chicken and Chow Mein are both excellent dishes that I would highly recommend to anyone who loves Chinese cuisine. The Orange Chicken is packed with flavor and has the perfect balance of savory and sweet flavors, while the Chow Mein has a wonderful texture and is full of fresh and flavorful ingredients. Together, they make for a truly satisfying meal that is sure to delight your taste buds.

I guess I can recommend this game. I had a lot of fun playing it with my friends for a good number of hours, but it does get dull after a while and the new content in season 2 wasn't nearly enough to keep me interested.

It is a fun game for the most part, but some of the minigames are just not fun at all and it didn't look like anything was being done to fix them. The new season brought almost no changes to existing maps, and 4 new games. I liked the new race, thought wall guys was ok, but I'd groan every time the new egg or hoop game got selected.

Also, I get that its a goofy bean man game where you're supposed to be clumsy and it shouldn't be taken too seriously, but it does get annoying when whether you win a game is out of your hands or not fair. Getting your tail sniped from lag in tail tag is annoying, having a single hiccup or getting unlucky and having a ball fall on your head in fall mountain guarantees a loss, for the ring game you need to get lucky and have them drop near you, and whichever team has the weakest start in the egg game is pretty much guaranteed to lose. 

I'd say I have a lot to complain about with this game, but it is a lot of fun for a while when you start playing it so I can still overall recommend it. I sadly don't think it's shown itself to have long lasting appeal though

Season 3 update:

They added a lot of new stuff this season, and it was enough to get me to hold my interest for a little while this time. However, I feel like the clunkiness of the game that started off as a fun element wears off and gets annoying after a while. I've gotten a bit tired of how much you stumble and trip around, and a couple bad minigames are enough to ruin a set, so I don't think I'm going to be revisiting this much now

Season 6 or something update idk:
A lot of things are much better now! Playing in squads is great, and *most* bad games aren't in anymore while the new games are all pretty solid. No more losing to BS in later rounds with tip toe and fall mountain :)

Fall Guys is a multiplayer party game that combines elements of platforming and battle royale games. The game features a variety of mini-games in which players compete against each other to be the last one standing and win the coveted crown.

The game's graphics and visuals are bright and colorful, with cute character designs and whimsical environments that create a lighthearted and fun atmosphere. The game's sound design is also well-done, with upbeat music and sound effects that add to the overall fun and silly vibe of the game.

The game's gameplay mechanics are simple yet addictive, with easy-to-learn controls and a variety of different mini-games that keep the gameplay fresh and engaging. The game's multiplayer aspect also adds to the fun, as players can compete against each other and engage in friendly rivalry.

One potential downside of the game is its lack of depth and replay value. Once players have experienced all the mini-games, the game may start to feel repetitive and lose its appeal. Additionally, the game's reliance on luck in certain mini-games may frustrate some players.

Overall, Fall Guys is a fun and lighthearted multiplayer game that offers a unique and engaging experience. The game's charming visuals and sound design, as well as its addictive gameplay mechanics, make it a must-play for fans of party games. However, its lack of depth and reliance on luck may make it feel somewhat shallow for some players. I would rate Fall Guys a 4 out of 5 for its fun and addictive gameplay.

The game's colorful and whimsical design is an instant mood-lifter, and the wacky obstacles and challenges provide endless entertainment. Whether you're dodging giant fruit or trying to navigate a chaotic obstacle course, Fall Guys keeps you on your toes and keeps the laughs coming.

Of course, the game's physics can be a bit wonky at times - I'm pretty sure my bean-shaped character has defied the laws of gravity on more than one occasion. But honestly, that's part of the fun. It's like the game is in on the joke, and we're all just along for the ride.

One downside is that the matchmaking can be a bit hit-or-miss at times, with occasional long wait times or connection issues. But honestly, I'm willing to overlook that for the pure joy that Fall Guys brings.

Overall, I'd give Fall Guys a funny and fun 5 out of 5 - it's the perfect game to play with friends or to unwind after a long day. Just be prepared to lose a few brain cells from all the laughter.

Fall Guys is a fun, easy, family-friendly royale-type game. Would I recommend it? Yes, but the biggest thing that ticks me off about it is that I didn't get the game for free like most of the people playing now. Just a few months ago, the game cost a full twenty bucks, and I purchased it at that price. I bought the game a month or two before it was announced that Fall Guys was becoming free to play, and even though I received some passes, it wasn't twenty dollar's worth. Now the game is filled with players who either payed money for the nice items or just pretty much wear the free, basic stuff. Fall Guys isn't pay to play, as you can only buy clothes, but if you won't put money into this game, your choices of attire are pretty lame. However, this game is still fun, even if it is filled with noobs. All events and levels are available without purchases. So, yes, I do recommend it (for new players, but Epic Games did a bad job here).

That means you have to grind so much of the game just to get each currency in the battle pass. A battle pass here costs 1000 of the currency and gives 300 of the currency for every battle pass, but the last 100 is at the end of the pass, meaning you need to devote so much of your time for mindless grinding while also having to deal with the matchmaking I mentioned from earlier, equalling a shit time that is overcomplicated than the game before it sucked. One of the game's key strengths is its accessibility. The game is easy to pick up and play, with simple controls and a straightforward objective: to be the last bean-shaped character standing. The game's cartoonish graphics and silly sound effects also add to the game's overall charm and appeal.

Another strength of Fall Guys is its replayability. With a variety of game modes, maps, and randomized obstacles, no two games are exactly the same. The game also features a leveling system and cosmetic rewards, providing players with a sense of progression and accomplishment.

However, the game does have some weaknesses. The gameplay can sometimes feel repetitive, especially after playing for an extended period of time. The game's reliance on luck and chance can also be frustrating for players who prefer games that are more skill-based. Additionally, the game's servers can sometimes be unstable, resulting in lag or disconnections.

"Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout" is a delightfully fun and addictive multiplayer game that will keep you entertained for hours on end. The game's colorful and cartoonish aesthetic, coupled with its engaging gameplay, make it a standout title in the battle royale genre.

The game's premise is simple yet effective, as players compete against each other in various obstacle courses and challenges, with the goal of being the last one standing. The game's controls are easy to learn, but mastering each obstacle and avoiding the other players can be challenging and rewarding.

One of the most enjoyable aspects of "Fall Guys" is the way it encourages players to be creative and strategic in their approach to each challenge. With multiple paths and options for completing each obstacle, the game encourages players to experiment and find the most effective strategy for their play style.

Beyond its engaging gameplay, "Fall Guys" is also a visually appealing game, with its colorful and whimsical art style adding to the game's fun and lighthearted tone.

Overall, "Fall Guys: Ultimate Knockout" is a fantastic game that is well worth your time. Its addictive gameplay, creative challenges, and charming aesthetic make it a standout title in the battle royale genre, and one that is sure to keep you entertained for hours on end.

This game has been consistently problematic, even though it is a free-to-play game, it is not acceptable to have such a large number of issues, especially considering that it has been a paid game for so long. The game is plagued with inconsistencies, bugs, and lag, which can give players an unfair advantage. Killing other players is far too easy, and suicide is even easier, which can be frustrating for players who lose because someone decided to kill themselves and take the player with them. Accidental kills occur frequently due to poor collision detection, and the physics in the game are often unreliable, leading to unavoidable issues. In its current state, I cannot recommend this game even if it were free, as it is simply a mess. While the game may have had some fixes in the past, it seems that those efforts were short-lived, and the game has only deteriorated further.

Oh. my. God. this game has been a rollercoaster of emotions, from pure joy to slightly less pure joy and then simply sadness, i can't put into words the happiness highs that this game has given me, but i also cant explain how sad this game makes me feel...
The negative:
Its like a person with dementia, a first, nothing is that bad, some signs of things going wrong are showing, in this case the first minor sign was s4's rampant dlcs, you say its not that bad, but it still sucks, the next sign is slightly stronger, those small discreptancies would usually just be small discreptancies but when you know that something will go wrong (since epic bought it) those small things make you think of whats coming next, s5.2 was the next sign, the new shitty UI reminded everybody of the corporateisation of the game, and yet we smiled through the pain, then s6 hit... the goddamn epic games accounts reminded everybody of where the game was going next, and then it struck """s1""", its not s1 and if they try to tell you it is its not, they can never replicate the pure joy of s1 and them saying that its s1 pisses me off, like they are trying to tell you it will be the same, but it isnt s1 its ss1 with microtransactions and so much bullshit that even if its free, for older players it doesnt justify what they have done to the game, *look at what they have done to my boy*, they have turned this game into a cash cow, all of a sudden a previously 16 pound game is now selling you two legendary skins for ¬£26 ¬£10 MORE THAN THE GAME WHEN IT WAS PAID, WHAT THE FRICK??? THEY EXPECT PEOPLE TO PAY THAT?????? anyone who actually buys these skins are fools, they are playing right into epic game's plan, ruin the game game and then make you pay for it... WHAT??? and i know mf's who are actually buying the skins, I KNOW PEOPLE WHO HAVE SPENT ¬£65 ON FUCKING SKINS, PAYING A COMPANY WHICH IS DIRECTLY SCREWING THEM OVER, WHAT?!?!?!??
The positive: 
This game's older seasons s1-s5.1 were goddamn GOLD, they were an example of some of the highest order of game design, seriously a fucking master piece, grinding out crowns in s3-5.1 was so fun and even though there werent many players, it was a loveley tight knit community, these seasons are the reason i still play today, because in my mind i trick into believing that its as good as it was then, and even though im telling you its not, i still can't accept it in my real mind, i still long for old fall guys, when it was funny bean game, when the game was decent and it was just "ohoho flal gu ded gam!! heheh lel jk this game is good!!" i still long for a time when there was a wonder around getting a win, and when those wins actually counted for anything, when you could get kudos through playing and when you could spend crowns on the shop, seriously listening to some for the older ost tracks makes me want to cry, i love this game, but what they have done to it isnt justifiable, oh yeah, this game's ost, for being a battle royale about beans, this games music is so good, its just so exciting and happy, too bad i cant feel happy because my favourite game is ruined.

Fall Guys is an incredibly fun and addictive game that will keep you entertained for hours on end. The game is a delightful mix of platforming and party games that will challenge your reflexes, timing, and strategic thinking.

The graphics are bright, colorful, and cartoonish, which adds to the game's charm and accessibility. The controls are simple and intuitive, so even if you're new to gaming, you'll be able to pick up the game quickly and start having fun.

The game's premise is simple: you play as a wobbly, bean-shaped character who must compete against other players in a series of obstacle courses and party games. The courses are varied and challenging, and you never know what's coming next. The party games are equally entertaining, and they range from soccer matches to memory games.

One of the things that makes Fall Guys so addictive is its unpredictability. You never know what's going to happen next, and that keeps you on your toes. The game is also very replayable, as each course is randomized, so no two runs are ever the same.

The game also has a great sense of humor. From the goofy sound effects to the ridiculous costumes you can unlock for your character, Fall Guys is just a lot of fun. The game also has a great social aspect, as you can play with friends or with strangers from around the world.

Overall, Fall Guys is a fantastic game that is well worth the price of admission. It's easy to pick up and play, but it's also challenging enough to keep you coming back for more. The game's mix of platforming and party games is a winning combination, and the bright, colorful graphics and silly sense of humor make it a joy to play. If you're looking for a fun, lighthearted game to play with friends or by yourself, Fall Guys is definitely worth checking out.

This is a MMO, 3D platformer, party game in which 60 players compete in mini-games/elimination rounds against each other until 1 man (or 1 team) is left standing. All players are awarded with in-game currency based on their performances. The currency are then used to buy cosmetic items for one's character or name tag from the in-game store, which rotates its merchandise daily. The appearance & vibe of this game is very light-hearted & goofy, but yet the gameplay can become surprisingly frustrating as the little character you control moves as clumsily as a toddler. 

The game is a fun time killer, but I don't think it would hold a gamer's interest for long term, unless that person has a tendency to be a collector, aka: a loot hoarder. This multi-player game, unfortunately, does not support voice or text chat, which is a MAJOR LET-DOWN for any multi-player game. Without friends to group up with & a 3rd party app such as Discord to provide voice chat, your communications with the other 59 random players are limited to the in-game taunt animations, which people tend to ignore. 

If you have friends who already own this game, the purchase will definitely be worth it if you guys play regularly with a 3rd party voice chat app to cheer or heckle each other. Otherwise, the replayability of this game will be dependent on how much of a loot hoarder you are.
